comments.body: This is just a very small layer over the s3 package. Do we gain much from having this?  I feel like this could just be a little code that's part of a util package (or something) in the apply-url-service where it's called from now. I'm not saying it's unnecessary but it I don't really think it belongs here.

Maybe I'm missing something but it looks like a instance of the middleware object is "newed" when the router is loaded https://github.com/cbdr/cbax-apply-url-service/blob/0878ecd1c51f5247d38910d91969508e8d43cf4d/router/router.go#L25. I would assume that only happens once during the app's life cycle. But then for each run through any of your middelware chains it looks the .Data property is getting set on a global reference by data that is specific to a particular request and middleware execution. https://github.com/cbdr/cbax-apply-url-service/blob/middleware/middleware/middleware.go#L85

Does my question make sense?

Hey all. This pull request is intended to fix a site issue here on the Rapid Response side of things (CSI258766). The issue is as follows: sometimes, certain Luceo clients will define 'resume' as 'CV' depending on their language, which leads to undefined attachment types (because the endpoint for attachment types will contain 'CV').

I'm aware that this is not the most elegant of solutions, but after discussing with Rosalie Deletre (a member of the Luceo team), this was the best solution we agreed upon. I'm open to suggestions and/or comments. (I don't like long ternary operators, either, but it's the most "elegant" solution I could find.)

I'll see if I can talk to them about this today. I agree that it would be best handled on their side, and I'm not sure why their web service for attachment types doesn't always guarantee that 'resume' is present instead of 'CV'. I remember one of their proposed solutions would be to simply use 'resume' instead of a numeric ID, but it seems like that would make the attachment type web service pointless.

I'm going to write a new pull request (I think), but I would like to know what your thoughts are on the potential fix. I know that cbax-apply-platform simply passes in filetype as a string and attempts to match it against the IDs returned from the Luceo endpoint, so perhaps we should just check here for "resume" or "cover letter" and manually map it to 2 or 3? It would bypass the ref/attachment-type/candidate/ endpoint but it might be the only solution we have in the meantime.
Now I'm wondering if the logger should be angular agnostic...
